3. Description of study (provided by SCORE). 
RR TEAM INSTRUCTIONS: ​This description has been provided by SCORE. Please review and 
make a SCORE project coordinator aware of any edits, additions, and corrections you would 
suggest to the paragraph. You are free to add additional descriptions of your project in a 
separate paragraph.  
 
We selected the claim that, consistent with the hypothesis that Asian category norms help explain 
high Asian-American capital accumulation, primed Asian-American subjects make more patient 
choices than Asian-American control subjects. This reflects the following statement from the paper's 
abstract: "When we make ethnic identity salient to Asian-American subjects, they make more patient 
choices." The claim is tested by regressing participants’ reservation log continuously compounded 
interest rate and risk premium on an experimental condition dummy. Table 2 presents formal 
regression evidence on priming effects, incorporating price information. Result in Table 2 that’s 
selected is in the Column of “Log interest rate” and “Asians”. Focal independent variable is “Ethnicity 
salient." Column 1 of Table 2 confirms that the interest rate required by Asians to defer payment falls 
dramatically when Asian ethnic identity is made salient, coefficient for “Ethnicity salient” is -1.4165 
with Huber-White standard errors clustered by subject of 0.3783, significant at the 1 percent level. 
 
 
 
 

 
4. Hypotheses (provided by SCORE with possible RR team additions) 
RR TEAM INSTRUCTIONS:​ ​The focal test for SCORE is indicated as H*. If you will test 
additional hypotheses (or use alternate analyses) that help you to evaluate the claim your 
replication/reproduction is testing, number them H1, H2, H3 etc. (You can place H* in the list 
wherever makes sense). Please make sure that any additional hypotheses are logical 
deductions/operationalizations of the selected SCORE claim or are necessary to properly 
